FerroFlux Systems docs · v2.4 GitHub Releases Status Documentation getting-started api-reference configuration changelog troubleshooting On This Page 1 · Install 2 · Configure Broker 3 · Register Device 4 · Push First Reading 5 · Verify Dashboard Resources SDK Source CLI Reference Examples docs / getting-started Getting Started A five-step walkthrough to install the FerroFlux SDK v2.4, provision your first MQTT broker profile, register an embedded device, push a sensor reading, and verify it lands in the operator dashboard. Prerequisites ·  Rust toolchain 1.74+, a reachable FerroFlux Gateway (self-hosted or cloud), and a valid FFX_API_TOKEN exported in your shell. 1 Install the SDK & CLI Install the ferroflux command-line tool and the Rust SDK from crates.io. The CLI is statically linked and ships with the embedded gateway shim used in steps 3–5. bash # install the CLI globally cargo install ferroflux-cli --version "2.4.0" # add the SDK to your project cargo add ferroflux-sdk@ 2.4 --features "mqtt,tls" 2 Configure a Broker Profile Profiles are declared in ferroflux.flux and define how the SDK reaches your MQTT broker. The generator scaffolds a sane default for TLS on port 8883. flux # ferroflux.flux broker "primary" {
  host         = "mqtts://broker.ferroflux.io" port         = 8883 tls          = true client_id    = "edge-${HOSTNAME}" keepalive_s  = 30 retention    = "7d" } 3 Register a Device Each physical sensor is registered against a schema. The CLI returns a device handle ( dev_… ) and a one-time provisioning secret. Store the secret in your secure enclave or HSM. bash ferroflux devices register \
  --name "floor-3-temp-01" \
  --schema "thermal/v2" \
  --broker "primary" \
  --tags "site=oslo,line=A" # → dev_8f3a21c0  (secret: ffx_sk_••••••••••••) 4 Push Your First Reading Open a stream from your Rust application and emit a typed sample. The SDK batches and compresses readings transparently; flush().await guarantees durability before continuing. rust use ferroflux_sdk::{Client, Reading, schema::Thermal}; #[tokio::main] async fn main () -> anyhow::Result<()> { let client = Client:: from_env (). await ?; let mut stream = client. stream ( "dev_8f3a21c0" ). await ?;

    stream. push (Reading::<Thermal> {
        celsius: 21.4 ,
        humidity: 0.38 ,
        ts:       chrono::Utc:: now (),
    }). await ?;

    stream. flush (). await ?;
    Ok(())
} 5 Verify in the Dashboard The CLI's tail subcommand streams live readings as they ingress the gateway. If you see your sample echoed within 2 seconds, you're done — the same data is now visible in the operator dashboard under Devices → floor-3-temp-01 . bash ferroflux streams tail dev_8f3a21c0 --since 1m # 14:22:08.114  thermal/v2  celsius=21.4  humidity=0.38  ✓ ingested Note DEPRECATED The legacy ferroflux verify --device flow used in v1.x has been removed; use streams tail instead. © 2025 FerroFlux Systems · docs build a1f3e92 License · Privacy · Contact On This Page 1 · Install 2 · Configure Broker 3 · Register Device 4 · Push First Reading 5 · Verify Dashboard
